eph |title=Diary Kept at the Siege of Louisburg, March 15\u2013August 14, 1745 |date=1910 |publisher=J. Wilson and Son |location=Cambridge |page=13 |others=notes and introduction by Samuel A. Green |url=https://archive.org/details/diarykeptatsieg00greegoog/page/n19}}<br>{{bullet}}{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_2BGAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA218&lpg=PA218&dq=Captain+Richard+Edwards+(Princess+Mary,+60+guns)#v=onepage&q=Captain+Richard+Edwards+(Princess+Mary,+60+guns)&f=false|title=Naval Chronology: Or, An Historical Summary of Naval & Maritime Events, from the Time of the Romans, to the Treaty of Peace, 1802|first=Isaac|last=Schomberg|date=December 26, 1802|publisher=T. Egerton|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* Captain Richard Tiddleman (T. Somers) (Superbe, 415 men, 60 guns)\n* Captain Philip Durell (Eltham, 250 men, 40 guns)\n* Captain W. J? Calmady (Launceston, 250 men, 40 guns)\n* Captain James Douglas (then Capt. W. Montague) (Mermaid, 250 men, 40 guns)\n\nJoined from England 22-23 May\n* Captain Frederick Cornwall (Hector, 40 guns)\n* Captain Richard Edwards (Princess Mary, 60 guns)\n\nJoined from England 10-11 June\n* Captain John Hore/ Hoar (D. Hare) (Canterbury, 60 guns);\n* Captain J. Brett (Sunderland, 60 guns);\n* Captain J. Crickshanke (Lark, 40 guns);\n* Capt. F. Geary  (Capt. Kemp) ([[HMS Chester (1743)|Chester]], 50 guns)\n* Capt. James Douglas (Vigilant, 64 guns) - Former prize taken 18 May\n* Captain Clark Gayton (Bien Aime, 30 guns) - former prize\n* Captain Britt (Sunderland, 60 guns)\n\n=== Massachusetts Naval Forces ===\n* Captain Edward Tyng (Ship Massachusetts frigate, 150 men, 20 guns)\n* Captain Jonathan Snelling (Molineux frigate, 150 men, 20 guns)\n* Captain George Griffith (Caesar, 70 men, 14 guns)\n* Captain [[John Rous]]e (Shirley Galley, 150 men, 20 guns)\n* Captain Joseph Smithers/ Smythurst (Snow [[Prince of Orange (ship)]], 80 men, 14 guns - sank in storm)\n* Captain William Fletcher (Brig Boston Packet, 16 guns; Wattering)\n* Captain [[David Donahew]] {{KIA}} (Sloop, 12 guns)\n* Captain Thomas Saunders (sloop, 8 guns)\n* Captain Bosch (sloop, 8 guns)\n\n=== Other Naval Forces ===\n* Captain Griffin (Rhode Island sloop, 20 guns)\n* Captain Thompson (Connecticut vessel, 16 guns)\n* Captain John Prentice (Defence, Connecticut vessel, 12 guns, 100 men)\n* Captain John Furnell (Fernald), (Abigail, 14 or 10 guns) - New Hampshire sloop\n* Captain [[Daniel Fones]] ([[Tartar (ship)]], 14 guns) - Rhode Island sloop<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=8aVFAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA155&lpg=PA155&dq=Captain+Daniel+Fones+(Tartar,#v=onepage&q=Captain%20Daniel%20Fones%20(Tartar%2C&f=false | title=Records of the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations, in New England: 1741-1756| last1=Bartlett| first1=John Russell| year=1860}}</ref>\n\n== Other British Military Personnel ==\n<gallery>\nFile:John Breynton.png|[[John Breynton]]\nFile:Winckworth Tonge, Old Burying Ground, Halifax, Nova Scotia.jpg|[[Winckworth Tonge]], d. 1792, [[Old Burying Ground (Halifax, Nova Scotia)]]\nFile:Jonathan Snelling, Old Burying Ground, Halifax, Nova Scotia.jpg|Colonel Jonathan Snelling's son, d. 1782,[[Old Burying Ground (Halifax, Nova Scotia)]] <ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Harvard University]]|title=Letter from David Phips to Colonel Jonathan Snelling regarding escort of Governor Hutchinson to Harvard Commencement, 1773 July 12 |website=Colonial North America at Harvard |url=http://colonialnorthamerica.library.harvard.edu/spotlight/cna/catalog/012521312 |accessdate=6 February 2018}}<br>{{bullet}}{{harvp|Sabine|1847|page=625|loc=[https://archive.org/details/americanloyalist00sabiuoft/page/625]}}<br>{{bullet}}{{harvp|Sabine|1864|pages=320\u2013321|loc=[https://archive.org/details/biographicalske03sabigoog/page/n327]}}</ref>\nFile:Statue of william prescott in charlestown massachusetts.jpg|[[William Prescott]]\n</gallery>\n\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}<!-- Make list into flexible columns -->\n* [[Richard Jacques (military officer)|Richard Jacques]] {{KIA}}, 2nd Massachusetts Regiment (Maine)\n* [[James Gibson (seaman)|James Gibson]]\n* [[Samuel Whittemore]], 3rd Massachusetts Regiment\n* [[John Gorham (military officer)|John Gorham]]\n* [[John Henry Bastide]]\n* [[Hector Theophilus de Cramah\u00e9]]\n* [[Robert Denison]], Connecticut Regiment\n* [[Sir Charles Douglas, 1st Baronet]]\n* [[Bartholomew Green (printer, born 1699)|Bartholomew Green]]\n* [[Richard Gridley]] (engineer of the batteries)<ref>http://pictoumasons.org/library/CDN%20Masonic%20Research%20~%20Freemasonry%20at%20Louisbourg%20%5Bpdf%5D.pdf</ref>\n* [[Robert Hale (doctor)|Robert Hale]], 1st Massachusetts Regiment (Maine)\n* [[Abijah Willard]], 4th Massachusetts Regiment\n* [[Robert Prescott]]\n* [[Samuel Moody]]<ref>{{cite DCB |first=Alfred G. |last=Bailey |title=Moody, Samuel |volume=3 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/moody_samuel_3E.htm}}</ref>\n* [[James Monk (lawyer)|James Monk]], 1st Massachusetts Regiment (Maine)<ref>{{cite DCB |title=Monk, James |first=Phyllis R. |last=Blakeley |volume=3 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/monk_james_3E.html}}</ref>\n* [[Beamsley Perkins Glasier]], 5th Massachusetts Regiment<ref>{{cite DCB |title=Glasier, Beamsley Perkins |first=D. Murray |last=Young |volume=4 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/glasier_beamsley_perkins_4E.html}}</ref>\n* [[John Caleff]]<ref>{{cite DCB |title=Caleff, John |first=Ann Gorman |last=Condon |volume=5 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/caleff_john_5E.html}}</ref>\n* [[William Vaughan (soldier)|William Vaughan]]<ref>https://archive.org/details/curwensamuelj00curwrich/page/451</ref><ref>{{cite DCB |title=Vaughn, William |first=G.A. |last=Rawlyk |volume=3 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/vaughan_william_3E.html}}</ref>\n* [[Christopher Aldridge]]<ref>{{cite DCB |title=Aldridge, Christopher, (d. 1760) |first=William G. |last=Godfrey |volume=3 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/aldridge_christopher_1760_3E.html}}</ref>\n* [[Nathan Whiting]]<ref>http://pictoumasons.org/library/CDN%20Masonic%20Research%20~%20Freemasonry%20at%20Louisbourg%20%5Bpdf%5D.pdf</ref>\n* [[James Frye]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Legacy ==\n* [[Louisburg Square]] in Boston is named after the siege.\n* Vernon Street, [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]] was formerly known as Louisbourg Street.\n* Shirley Street, Halifax, Nova Scotia is named for Massachusetts Governor William Shirley.\n* Pepperell St. Halifax, Nova Scotia was named after Pepperrell\n* [[Pepperell, Massachusetts]] was named after William Pepperrell.\n* [[Warren, Rhode Island]] was named after British naval hero Admiral Sir Peter Warren.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Swiss regiment de Karrer]]\n* [[Military history of Nova Scotia]]\n* [[Louisbourg Garrison]]\n* [[Provincial troops in the French and Indian Wars]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Primary sources===\n* {{cite journal |last=Bidwell |first=Adonijah  |author-link=Adonijah Bidwell |title=Expeditions to Cape Breton: Journal of the Rev. Adonijah Bidwell, Chaplain of the Fleet |journal=The New England Historical and Genealogical Register and Antiquarian Journal |date=April 1873 |volume=27 |issue=2 |location=Boston |publisher=[[New England Historic Genealogical Society]] |pages=153\u2013160 |url=https://archive.org/details/newenglandhisto29unkngoog/page/n178 |ref=harv}}{{snd}} Also: {{Internet Archive|newenglandhistor1873wate|Expeditions to Cape Breton|n337}}\n* {{cite book |last=Bradstreet |first=Dudley |title=Diary kept by Lieut. Dudley Bradstreet of Groton, Mass., during the siege of Louisburg. April, 1745\u2013January, 1746 |publisher=J. Wilson and son |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |date=1897 |url=https://archive.org/details/diarykeptbylieut00brad|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bradstreet|first=Dudley|chapter=Diary kept by Lieut. Dudley Bradstreet of Groton, Mass., during the siege of Louisburg. April, 1745\u2013January, 1746|editor=Samuel Abbott Green|editor-link=Samuel Abbott Green|title=Three Military Diaries Kept by Groton Soldiers in Different Wars|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Nq4W3Grtmg0C&pg=PA1|year=1901|publisher=J. Wilson and son|location=Groton, Massachusetts|pages=1\u201339}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Cleaves |first=Benjanmin |title=Benjamin Cleaves's Journal of the Expedition to Louisburg, 1745 |journal=The New England Historical and Genealogical Register |location=Boston |volume=66 |date=April 1912 |pages=113\u2013124 |url=https://archive.org/details/newenglandhistor1912newe/page/113}}\n* {{cite book |last= Curwen |first=Samuel |editor=George Atkinson Ward |title=Journal and letters of the late Samuel Curwen, judge of Admiralty, etc., an American refugee in England from 1775-1784 |publisher=C. S. Francis and Co |location=New York |date=1842 |url=https://archive.org/details/curwensamuelj00curwrich}}\n* {{cite book |last=DeForest|first=Louis Effingham|title=Louisbourg Journals, 1745|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015005553774|year=1932|publisher=Society of Colonial Wars|location=New York|ref=harv}}{{snd}} Also: {{google books|GdCJ-zXK8mMC|Louisbourg Journals, 1745}} ({{ISBN|978-0-7884-1015-4}})\n* {{cite journal |last=Emerson |first=Joseph |title=Diary Kept at the Siege of Louisburg, March 15\u2013August 14, 1745 |journal=Proceedings of the Massachusetts Historical Society |date=October 1910 |url=https://archive.org/details/diarykeptatsieg00greegoog}}{{snd}} Also: {{google book|qzstAAAAYAAJ|Diary Kept at the Siege of Louisburg|page=65}}\n* {{cite book |last=Gibson|first=James|authorlink=James Gibson (seaman)|title=A Journal of the Late Siege by the Troops from North America, against the French at Cape Breton, the City of Louisbourg, and the Territories thereunto belonging|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=aeu.ark:/13960/t4vh69j9b|year=1745|publisher=J. Newbery|location=London}}{{snd}} Also: {{google books|6tVbAAAAQAAJ|A Journal of the Late Siege by the Troops from North America}}\n* {{cite journal |la