asons.org/library/CDN%20Masonic%20Research%20~%20Freemasonry%20at%20Louisbourg%20%5Bpdf%5D.pdf Freemasons at the Two Sieges of Louisbourg]\n* List of Soldiers, 1745, Collections of the Connecticut Historical Society 13: 76-80\n* [https://books.google.ca/books?id=Z2sFAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA259&lpg=PA259&dq=Captain+Nathaniel+Bosworth+louisburg&source=bl&ots=tRtjcDT5Aq&sig=ACfU3U2Y0b3ZiN94pX2ZMZ_cRfnGrMlbfw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwifsJad0s_mAhUm1VkKHYI8DBgQ6AEwCnoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Captain%20Nathaniel%20Bosworth%20louisburg&f=false Louisburg Soldiers (1745)]\n* [http://parkscanadahistory.com/series/saah/amateurs.pdf Siege of Louisbourg (1745) - Parks Canada]\n* [http://www.krausehouse.ca/krause/EricKrauseReports/LsbgJournals.html The Daily Journals, Diaries, Letters, and Accounts of Louisbourg and Isle Royale (1713-1768)]\n* [http://www.nfb.ca/film/louisbourg_under_siege/ ''Louisbourg Under Siege''], a [[National Film Board of Canada]] documentary\n* {{London Gazette|issue=8451|date=20 July 1745|page=5}}, details of the French surrender at Louisbourg\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Siege Of Louisbourg (1745)}}\n[[Category:1745 in Canada]]\n[[Category:1745 in New France]]\n[[Category:Sieges of the War of the Austrian Succession|Louisbourg 1745]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Military history of Acadia]]\n[[Category:Military history of New England]]\n[[Category:Military history of Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:New France]]\n[[Category:Pre-statehood history of Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Sieges involving France|Louisbourg 1745]]\n[[Category:Sieges involving Great Britain|Louisbourg 1745]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1745]]\n[[Category:Battles of King George's War]]\n", "name_user": "Snagemit", "label": "safe", "comment": "Infobox changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siege_of_Louisbourg_(1745)"}
{"title_page": "Corrour railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| name       = Corrour|symbol=rail\n| other_name = {{lang-gd|An Coire Odhar}}{{sfn|Brailsford|2017|loc=Gaelic/English Station Index}}\n| code       = CRR\n| image_name = Caledonian Sleeper At Corrour Station (17738023599).jpg\n| caption    = Corrour station\n| manager   = [[Abellio ScotRail]] \n| locale    = [[Loch Ossian]] \n| borough   = [[Highland (council area)|Highland]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|56.7602|-4.6907|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| platforms = 2\n<!-- |lowusage0506 = {{pad}} 9,885\n|lowusage0607 = {{increase}} 11,045\n|lowusage0708 = {{increase}} 13,226\n|lowusage0809 = {{decrease}} 12,724\n|lowusage0910 = {{decrease}} 12,280\n|lowusage1011 = {{increase}} 12,782\n|lowusage1112 = {{decrease}} 12,224\n|lowusage1213 = {{decrease}} 12,058\n|lowusage1314 = {{increase}} 13,138 -->\n|lowusage1415 = {{decrease}} 12,856\n|lowusage1516 = {{decrease}} 11,156\n|lowusage1617 = {{decrease}} 11,092\n|lowusage1718 = {{increase}} 13,302\n|lowusage1819 = {{increase}} 14,344\n|original  = [[West Highland Railway]]\n|pregroup  = [[North British Railway]]\n|postgroup = [[London and North Eastern Railway|LNER]]\n|years     = 7 August 1894\n|events    = Opened<ref name=butt>Butt (1995)</ref>\n|years1    =\n|events1   = \n|gridref   = NN356663\n|}}\n\n'''Corrour railway station''' is on the [[Crianlarich railway station|Crianlarich]]-[[Fort William railway station|Fort William]]/[[Mallaig railway station|Mallaig]] branch of the [[West Highland Line]]. It is situated near [[Loch Ossian]] on the [[Corrour Lodge#Corrour Estate|Corrour Estate]], [[Highland (council area)|Highland]] Region (formerly [[Inverness-shire]]), [[Scotland]].<ref name=\"NR\">Network Rail, http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/CRR/details.html</ref> It is the highest [[mainline (railway)|mainline]] [[train station|railway station]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"Canmore 105961\">{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/105961/corrour-station|title=Corrour Station - Canmore|website=Canmore.org.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> Its [[Scottish Gaelic]] name, displayed on signs at the station, is Coire Odhar, which means dun-coloured [[cirque|corrie]].\n\n== Location ==\nThe station is one of the most remote in the United Kingdom, at an isolated location on the northern edge of [[Rannoch Moor]].<ref>Mountain Moor and Loch, p114.</ref> It is not accessible by any public roads. The nearest road, the B846 road from [[Loch Rannoch]] to [[Rannoch railway station|Rannoch station]], is a ten-mile (16 km) walk away by hill track,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/uk/scotland/718838/Scotland-Walk-of-the-month.html|title=Scotland: Walk of the month|first=Christopher|last=Somerville|date=15 June 2001|accessdate=8 January 2018|website=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> although Rannoch station itself is only 7\u00bc route-miles (11.5 km) away by rail.<ref>British Rail Passenger Timetable, summer 1992, p1322</ref> Vehicular access is by a 15-mile (24km) private road from a little west of Moy Lodge on the A86. Until the late 1980s, the only electrical power at the station was provided by batteries. The only telephone was the railway's system which linked Corrour only to the adjacent signalboxes at Rannoch and [[Tulloch railway station|Tulloch]], which were on the public telephone system.<ref>Thomas, p 65</ref>\n \nAt 1,340 ft (408 m) above sea level<ref name=\"Canmore 105961\"/> the station provides a starting point for hill-walkers and [[Munro#Bagging the Munros|Munro-baggers]]. There is accommodation and a bar/restaurant available at the station<ref>Corrour Station House, West Word, August 2015 issue, https://www.westword.org.uk/august2015.html</ref> and an [[Scottish Youth Hostels Association|SYHA]] youth hostel just over a mile (2 km) away at the head of [[Loch Ossian]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syha.org.uk/where-to-stay/highlands/loch-ossian.aspx|title=Loch Ossian - SYHA Hostelling Scotland|website=Syha.org.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nCorrour station was built by the [[West Highland Railway]] between 1893 and 1894 on its line linking Glasgow with Fort William and was operated from its opening on 7 August 1894 by the [[North British Railway]].<ref>Thomas, chapters 3 and 4; dates from pp 64 and 170</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transporttrust.com/heritage-sites/heritage-detail/corrour-railway-station|title=Heritage Locations|website=Transporttrust.com|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> It has a [[passing loop]] around an [[island platform]] with a [[siding (rail)|siding]] on the east side. In common with the line\u2019s two other remote passing places, [[Gorton railway station (West Highland Line)|Gorton]] and [[Glen Douglas Halt railway station|Glen Douglas]], it was built with a tall [[Signalling control|signalbox]] and an adjacent low building in which the [[signalman (rail)|signalman]] lived.<ref>McGregor, p 39</ref><ref name=\"RHT\">{{cite web|title=Railway Heritage Trust, Annual Report and Accounts, 2015/2016|page=17|url=http://railwayheritagetrust.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/ANNUAL-REPORT-AND-ACCOUNTS-2015_16.pdf|format=PDF|website=Railwayheritagetrust.co.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> The adjacent low building (in Corrour's case) was also used as a [[General Post Office|sub post office]] from 15 December 1896 and a Post Office telegraph office from 16 August 1898; Corrour even qualified as a [[post town]].<ref name=\"Post Offices\">{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/ukpostofficesbycounty/home/scotland|title=Scotland - UK Post Offices by County|website=Sites.google.com|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>{{verification failed|date=November 2019}} Later the railway constructed a station house for the signalman on the east side of the tracks and the original building became purely office accommodation for the railway and the post office.<ref name=\"Canmore 563613\">{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/event/563613/|title=Recording Your Heritage Online - Canmore|website=Canmore.org.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nCorrour was originally intended<ref>Thomas p 135</ref> to be merely a passing place on the long section between Rannoch and Tulloch, called Luibruaridh (sic)<ref>''Mountain Moor & Loch'' p114</ref> after the nearest habitation, Luibruairidh, on the old [[Drovers' road|drove road]] between [[Rannoch]] and [[Spean Bridge]], about 1\u00bd miles (2 km) northwest of the passing place.<ref name=OS1>{{cite web|title=Ordnance Survey six-inch 1st edition (1843-1882)|publisher=National Library of Scotland|url=http://maps.nls.uk/view/74427181|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> However, from its opening its small island platform was used as a station and the name Corrour was also used<ref>''Mountain Moor & Loch'', distance table in frontispiece</ref> although Corrour Lodge at that time was where the drove road crossed Coire Odhar, some 5 miles (8 km) southeast of the station.<ref name=\"OS1\" /> However, when the station opened estate traffic was facilitated by the building of a mile-long (1.5 km) track connecting the station to the old drove road as it passed near the head of Loch Ossian.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jennifer G. |last=Robertson |title=An Archaeological Survey of Parts of Corrour Estate [etc] |date=December 2009 |url=https://librarylink.highland.gov.uk/LLFiles/208568/full_208568.pdf }}</ref>\n\nIn the early days there was so much estate business that the railway employed an extra clerkess during the [[driven grouse shooting|grouse]] season. It was theoretically a private station for the use of the estate but it was also used by the public from the start despite its not appearing in the public timetables until September 1934.<ref>Thomas pp 72,73</ref><ref>Thomas p 171 gives the date of its being open to the public as 15 September, a Saturday; Canmore 105961 gives 11 September 1934, a Tuesday, possibly following Butt</ref>\n[[File:Corrour railway station map 2017 v1.jpg|thumb|Map showing location of Corrour railway station with reference to other geographical features mentioned in the article]]\n\nIn 1897, the estate built a new lodge at the foot of Loch Ossian, 4\u00bd miles (7 km) northeast of the station. There was however no vehicular access to the lodge from the public road system so all goods (including vehicles) had to come and go by rail via Corrour station. Until the track along the south shore of Loch Ossian was built, the estate ran a small steamer from the lodge to the head of Loch Ossian (where Loch Ossian youth hostel is now) from which the station was only a little over a mile (2 km) away.<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=GDL00107|desc=Corrour Lodge|access-date=12 April 2019}}</ref> In 1972 the Forestry Commission built a private [[Macadam|macadamized]] road from the A86 at near Moy Lodge to Corrour Lodge, so for the first time there was vehicular access to the station, via Corrour Lodge and Moy Lodge, a total distance of 15 miles (24 km).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.corrour.co.uk/lodge/architecture-history/|title=Architecture & History - Corrour Estate - Highlands Scotland|website=Corrour.co.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nCorrour sub post and telegraph office closed on 5 March 1977.<ref name=\"Post Offices\"/>\n\nDuring the construction of the [[Lochaber hydroelectric scheme]] in the 1930s a small [[Train_station#Halt|halt]] was located at [[Fersit Halt railway station|Fersit]], between Corrour and Tulloch, about 2 miles (3 km) short of the latter.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n[[File:Scotland Corrour Station.jpg|thumb|Corrour station from the south in March 1982, showing the original station house and the footbridge before its removal to Rannoch]]\nSince November 1985, all passenger trains have used the original [[Rail directions#up and down|\u201cdown\u201d]] platform. The \"up\" loop remains and is serviceable but it is no longer used by passenger trains.<ref name=\"RHT\" /> There was originally a footbridge at Corrour station providing an exit to the east side, but it was moved to Rannoch station following the downgrading of the \"up\" loop at Corrour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/event/796121|title=Archaeology Notes - Canmore|website=Canmore.org.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> Passengers now cross the line by a [[Level crossings in the United Kingdom#Barrow crossing|barrow crossing]].<ref name=\"NR\"/>\n\nIn 1998/1999 Corrour Estate replaced the former signalman\u2019s house with a new station house. This included business premises and lodging for their managers and had electric power from a diesel generator.<ref name=\"Canmore 563613\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotlandmag.com/magazine/issue49/12009604.html|title=Magic of the Moor : Scotland Magazine Issue 49|website=Scotlandmag.com|accessdate=8 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116075315/http://www.scotlandmag.com/magazine/issue49/12009604.html|archive-date=16 November 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The station house subsequently had a number of tenants over the years becoming an independent hostel, an SYHA hostel (in addition to the SYHA\u2019s nearby hostel at Loch Ossian), and a restaurant. In 2015, the estate took over the running of the building and after closure for refurbishment reopened it as a bar and restaurant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jimsloire.blogspot.co.uk/2015/06/corrour-station-house-now-closed.html|title=Corrour Station House: now closed|website=Jimsloire.blogspot.co.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn 2012, the red stone chippings on the platform, which [[Network Rail]] acknowledged would be hazardous to wheelchair passengers, were replaced by a hard surface.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.covanburn.com/recent-projects.html|title=Recent Projects At Covanburn Contracts|first=|last=Covanburn.net|website=Covanburn.com|accessdate=8 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116081744/http://www.covanburn.com/recent-projects.html|archive-date=16 November 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Historic Scotland]] [[Listed building|listed]] the disused signalbox (called the \"old watchtower\" by Network Rail) and the adjacent building as [[Listed building#Scotland|Category C]] (the tall boxes at Gorton and Glen Douglas had been demolished).<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB52057|desc=Corrour Station, Waiting Room and Signal Box|cat=C|access-date=12 April 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref> Subsequently, Network Rail, in conjunction with the Corrour Estate and the Railway Heritage Trust, refurbished the signalbox and in 2016 the estate opened three guest rooms in it.<ref name=\"RHT\" />\n\n== Facilities ==\nThe 3-character code for Corrour is CRR.<ref name=\"NR\"/>\n\nCorrour is unstaffed and there are no ticket-issuing facilities, but there is a validator for a \"smartcard\" paperless card-based ticketing system. There are no departure announcements but there is WiFi, a telephone help point, an electronic departure display and a Caledonian Sleeper digital information point. There is a waiting room with bench seats and a cycle rack. The station is lit by electric lights.<ref name=\"NR\"/>\n\n== Services ==\n[[File:Corrour(2).jpg|thumb|left|A train to Mallaig]]\nCorrour station is now passenger-only and is served by regular [[Abellio ScotRail]] passenger trains between [[Glasgow Queen Street railway station|Glasgow Queen Street]] and Fort William/Mallaig. These local services run generally three times a day in each direction, but less frequently on Sundays (twice each way in summer, but just once in winter). In addition, Corrour is served by the [[Caledonian Sleeper]] service between Fort William and London [[Euston railway station|Euston]] via Glasgow Queen Street (Low Level) and [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Edinburgh]] (daily except Saturday nights in each direction). The journey from London to Corrour takes just under twelve hours. The sleeper also conveys seated coaches and can therefore also be used by regular West Highland passengers travelling to or from Glasgow or Edinburgh.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotrail.co.uk/plan-your-journey/timetables-and-routes|title=Scotrail Train Times - Plan your Journey|website=Scotrail.co.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> \nAlthough National Rail state that Corrour is a [[request stop]],<ref name=\"NR\"/> Scotrail's 2019-20 timetable shows it as a compulsory stop.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Abellio ScotRail Ltd |title=West Highlands Train Times |url=https://www.scotrail.co.uk/sites/default/files/assets/download_ct/20238_west_highlands.pdf |website=ScotRail.co.uk |publisher=Abellio ScotRail Ltd |accessdate=22 December 2019 |ref=timetable-201912 |pages=2-3 |format=pdf |date=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIts estimated usage of 14,344 (2018-19) made it the busiest station on the line north of [[Crianlarich railway station|Crianlarich]], apart from Fort William and Mallaig.\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line\n|next     = {{Stnlnk|Tulloch}}\n|previous = {{Stnlnk|Rannoch}}\n|route    = [[Abellio ScotRail]]<br /><small>[[West Highland Line]]</small>\n|col      = {{ScotRail colour}} }}\n{{rail line\n|previous = {{Stnlnk|Rannoch}}\n|next     = {{Stnlnk|Tulloch}}\n|route    = [[Caledonian Sleeper]]<br /><small>[[Caledonian Sleeper|Highland Caledonian Sleeper]]</small>\n|col      = {{CS color}} }}\n{{Historical Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line\n|previous = {{Stnlnk|Rannoch}}\n|next     = {{Stnlnk|Tulloch}}\n|route    = [[North British Railway]]<br /><small>[[West Highland Railway]]</small>\n|col      = {{NBR colour}} |lightcol={{NBR light}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n{{clear left}}\n\n== Signalling ==\n[[File:Corrour railway station.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Corrour station from the north, in April 2004]]\nThe [[signal box]], which had 13 levers, was situated to the south of the [[island platform]]. From the time of its opening in 1894, the West Highland Railway was worked throughout by the electric [[Token (railway signalling)|token system]]. The [[Railway semaphore signal|semaphore signals]] were removed in November 1985 in preparation for the introduction of [[Radio Electronic Token Block]] (RETB). At the same time, the loop [[points (rail)|points]] came under the control of [[Ground frame|ground frames]]. The RETB system was commissioned by [[British Rail]] between {{Stnlnk|Upper Tyndrum}} and [[Fort William Junction]] on 29 May 1988. This resulted in the closure of Corrour [[Railway signalling|signal]] box and others on that part of the route. The RETB is controlled from a Signalling Centre at [[Banavie railway station]].{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n== Cultural references ==\n\nThe station, and the nearby mountain [[Leum Uilleim]], gained fame when they were featured in a scene from the film ''[[Trainspotting (film)|Trainspotting]]''. It also appeared in the fourth episode of the 2010 [[BBC]] series ''[[Secret Britain]]''. The station also featured in the [[Young Guns (band)|Young Guns]] video for the single \"Weight of the World\". The station is the primary location in Jos Stelling's film ''[[De Wisselwachter]]''.  It was also visited by [[Paul Merton]] in Episode 3 of his [[Channel 4]] documentary series ''[[Paul Merton's Secret Stations]]''.<ref>[http://www.channel4.com/info/press/programme-information/paul-mertons-secret-stations] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160530232046/http://www.channel4.com/info/press/programme-information/paul-mertons-secret-stations |date=30 May 2016 }} ''Channel 4 Programme Information'' website; Retrieved 16 May 2016</ref>\n\nThe route south from Corrour across the Moor of Rannoch to Rannoch Station itself was used as a filming location in the ''Harry Potter'' films where a [[Death Eater]] was seen to stand between the rails with an outstretched arm, to bring the approaching Hogwarts Express to a stand for the train to be inspected. Warner Brothers spent a couple of days with equipment based at Rannoch to facilitate the filming sequences.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Brailsford |editor-first=Martyn |title=Railway Track Diagrams 1: Scotland & Isle of Man |edition=6th |date=December 2017 |origyear=1987 |publisher=Trackmaps |location=Frome |isbn=978-0-9549866-9-8 |ref=harv }}\n* {{Butt-Stations}}\n* {{Jowett-Atlas}}\n* {{Jowett-Nationalised}}\n* McGregor, John A., ''All Stations to Mallaig'', D. Bradford Barton Ltd, 1st edition, 1982. {{ISBN|0-85153-426-0}}\n* ''Mountain Moor and Loch: on the Route of the West Highland Railway'', Sir Joseph Causton & Sons, 1st edition, 1894\n* Thomas, John, ''The West Highland Railway'', David St John Thomas, 3rd edition, 1992, {{ISBN|0-946537-22-4}}\n* {{Quail-1}}\n* [http://www.scotlandthemovie.com/movies/rantrain.html Scotland: the Movie Location Guide \u2013 Trainspotting, Rannoch Moor] Information on the station as it appears in \"Trainspotting\".\n* [https://www.railscot.co.uk/West_Highland_Railway/index.php] Further details on the station.\n* [http://www.hiddeneurope.co.uk/article_info.php?articles_id=249 Hidden Europe magazine] \u2013 an article about Corrour from ''Hidden Europe'' magazine\n* Article on the station by Ian Futers, four pages including track plan, photos, and description in [https://archive.is/20070503043613/http://www.peco-uk.com/Publications/RailwayM_this.htm ''Railway Modeller''] magazine for April 2008\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p53ECuJFtD0 Annotated video of Corrour station and restaurant]\n* {{Commonscat-inline|Corrour railway station}}\n\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Highland (council area)]]\n[[Category:Former North British Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1894]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by Abellio ScotRail]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by Caledonian Sleeper]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Great Britain without road access]]\n[[Category:Railway request stops in Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Listed railway stations in Scotland]]\n[[Category:1894 establishments in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| name       = Corrour|symbol=rail\n| other_name = {{lang-gd|An Coire Odhar}}{{sfn|Brailsford|2017|loc=Gaelic/English Station Index}}\n| code       = CRR\n| image_name = Caledonian Sleeper At Corrour Station (17738023599).jpg\n| caption    = Corrour station\n| manager   = [[Abellio ScotRail]] \n| locale    = [[Loch Ossian]] \n| borough   = [[Highland (council area)|Highland]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|56.7602|-4.6907|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| platforms = 2\n<!-- |lowusage0506 = {{pad}} 9,885\n|lowusage0607 = {{increase}} 11,045\n|lowusage0708 = {{increase}} 13,226\n|lowusage0809 = {{decrease}} 12,724\n|lowusage0910 = {{decrease}} 12,280\n|lowusage1011 = {{increase}} 12,782\n|lowusage1112 = {{decrease}} 12,224\n|lowusage1213 = {{decrease}} 12,058\n|lowusage1314 = {{increase}} 13,138 -->\n|lowusage1415 = {{decrease}} 12,856\n|lowusage1516 = {{decrease}} 11,156\n|lowusage1617 = {{decrease}} 11,092\n|lowusage1718 = {{increase}} 13,302\n|lowusage1819 = {{increase}} 14,344\n|original  = [[West Highland Railway]]\n|pregroup  = [[North British Railway]]\n|postgroup = [[London and North Eastern Railway|LNER]]\n|years     = 7 August 1894\n|events    = Opened<ref name=butt>Butt (1995)</ref>\n|years1    =\n|events1   = \n|gridref   = NN356663\n|}}\n\n'''Corrour railway station''' is on the [[Crianlarich railway station|Crianlarich]]-[[Fort William railway station|Fort William]]/[[Mallaig railway station|Mallaig]] branch of the [[West Highland Line]]. It is situated near [[Loch Ossian]] on the [[Corrour Lodge#Corrour Estate|Corrour Estate]], [[Highland (council area)|Highland]] Region (formerly [[Inverness-shire]]), [[Scotland]].<ref name=\"NR\">Network Rail, http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/CRR/details.html</ref> It is the highest [[mainline (railway)|mainline]] [[train station|railway station]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"Canmore 105961\">{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/105961/corrour-station|title=Corrour Station - Canmore|website=Canmore.org.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> Its [[Scottish Gaelic]] name, displayed on signs at the station, is Coire Odhar, which means dun-coloured [[cirque|corrie]].\n\n== Location ==\nThe station is one of the most remote in the United Kingdom, at an isolated location on the northern edge of [[Rannoch Moor]].<ref>Mountain Moor and Loch, p114.</ref> It is not accessible by any public roads. The nearest road, the B846 road from [[Loch Rannoch]] to [[Rannoch railway station|Rannoch station]], is a ten-mile (16 km) walk away by hill track,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/uk/scotland/718838/Scotland-Walk-of-the-month.html|title=Scotland: Walk of the month|first=Christopher|last=Somerville|date=15 June 2001|accessdate=8 January 2018|website=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> although Rannoch station itself is only 7\u00bc route-miles (11.5 km) away by rail.<ref>British Rail Passenger Timetable, summer 1992, p1322</ref> Vehicular access is by a 15-mile (24km) private road from a little west of Moy Lodge on the A86. Until the late 1980s, the only electrical power at the station was provided by batteries. The only telephone was the railway's system which linked Corrour only to the adjacent signalboxes at Rannoch and [[Tulloch railway station|Tulloch]], which were on the public telephone system.<ref>Thomas, p 65</ref>\n \nAt 1,340 ft (408 m) above sea level<ref name=\"Canmore 105961\"/> the station provides a starting point for hill-walkers and [[Munro#Bagging the Munros|Munro-baggers]]. There is accommodation and a bar/restaurant available at the station<ref>Corrour Station House, West Word, August 2015 issue, https://www.westword.org.uk/august2015.html</ref> and an [[Scottish Youth Hostels Association|SYHA]] youth hostel just over a mile (2 km) away at the head of [[Loch Ossian]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syha.org.uk/where-to-stay/highlands/loch-ossian.aspx|title=Loch Ossian - SYHA Hostelling Scotland|website=Syha.org.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nCorrour station was built by the [[West Highland Railway]] between 1893 and 1894 on its line linking Glasgow with Fort William and was operated from its opening on 7 August 1894 by the [[North British Railway]].<ref>Thomas, chapters 3 and 4; dates from pp 64 and 170</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transporttrust.com/heritage-sites/heritage-detail/corrour-railway-station|title=Heritage Locations|website=Transporttrust.com|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> It has a [[passing loop]] around an [[island platform]] with a [[siding (rail)|siding]] on the east side. In common with the line\u2019s two other remote passing places, [[Gorton railway station (West Highland Line)|Gorton]] and [[Glen Douglas Halt railway station|Glen Douglas]], it was built with a tall [[Signalling control|signalbox]] and an adjacent low building in which the [[signalman (rail)|signalman]] lived.<ref>McGregor, p 39</ref><ref name=\"RHT\">{{cite web|title=Railway Heritage Trust, Annual Report and Accounts, 2015/2016|page=17|url=http://railwayheritagetrust.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/ANNUAL-REPORT-AND-ACCOUNTS-2015_16.pdf|format=PDF|website=Railwayheritagetrust.co.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> The adjacent low building (in Corrour's case) was also used as a [[General Post Office|sub post office]] from 15 December 1896 and a Post Office telegraph office from 16 August 1898; Corrour even qualified as a [[post town]].<ref name=\"Post Offices\">{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/ukpostofficesbycounty/home/scotland|title=Scotland - UK Post Offices by County|website=Sites.google.com|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>{{verification failed|date=November 2019}} Later the railway constructed a station house for the signalman on the east side of the tracks and the original building became purely office accommodation for the railway and the post office.<ref name=\"Canmore 563613\">{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/event/563613/|title=Recording Your Heritage Online - Canmore|website=Canmore.org.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nCorrour was originally intended<ref>Thomas p 135</ref> to be merely a passing place on the long section between Rannoch and Tulloch, called Luibruaridh (sic)<ref>''Mountain Moor & Loch'' p114</ref> after the nearest habitation, Luibruairidh, on the old [[Drovers' road|drove road]] between [[Rannoch]] and [[Spean Bridge]], about 1\u00bd miles (2 km) northwest of the passing place.<ref name=OS1>{{cite web|title=Ordnance Survey six-inch 1st edition (1843-1882)|publisher=National Library of Scotland|url=http://maps.nls.uk/view/74427181|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> However, from its opening its small island platform was used as a station and the name Corrour was also used<ref>''Mountain Moor & Loch'', distance table in frontispiece</ref> although Corrour Lodge at that time was where the drove road crossed Coire Odhar, some 5 miles (8 km) southeast of the station.<ref name=\"OS1\" /> However, when the station opened estate traffic was facilitated by the building of a mile-long (1.5 km) track connecting the station to the old drove road as it passed near the head of Loch Ossian.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jennifer G. |last=Robertson |title=An Archaeological Survey of Parts of Corrour Estate [etc] |date=December 2009 |url=https://librarylink.highland.gov.uk/LLFiles/208568/full_208568.pdf }}</ref>\n\nIn the early days there was so much estate business that the railway employed an extra clerkess during the [[driven grouse shooting|grouse]] season. It was theoretically a private station for the use of the estate but it was also used by the public from the start despite its not appearing in the public timetables until September 1934.<ref>Thomas pp 72,73</ref><ref>Thomas p 171 gives the date of its being open to the public as 15 September, a Saturday; Canmore 105961 gives 11 September 1934, a Tuesday, possibly following Butt</ref>\n[[File:Corrour railway station map 2017 v1.jpg|thumb|Map showing location of Corrour railway station with reference to other geographical features mentioned in the article]]\n\nIn 1897, the estate built a new lodge at the foot of Loch Ossian, 4\u00bd miles (7 km) northeast of the station. There was however no vehicular access to the lodge from the public road system so all goods (including vehicles) had to come and go by rail via Corrour station. Until the track along the south shore of Loch Ossian was built, the estate ran a small steamer from the lodge to the head of Loch Ossian (where Loch Ossian youth hostel is now) from which the station was only a little over a mile (2 km) away.<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=GDL00107|desc=Corrour Lodge|access-date=12 April 2019}}</ref> In 1972 the Forestry Commission built a private [[Macadam|macadamized]] road from the A86 at near Moy Lodge to Corrour Lodge, so for the first time there was vehicular access to the station, via Corrour Lodge and Moy Lodge, a total distance of 15 miles (24 km).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.corrour.co.uk/lodge/architecture-history/|title=Architecture & History - Corrour Estate - Highlands Scotland|website=Corrour.co.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nCorrour sub post and telegraph office closed on 5 March 1977.<ref name=\"Post Offices\"/>\n\nDuring the construction of the [[Lochaber hydroelectric scheme]] in the 1930s a small [[Train_station#Halt|halt]] was located at [[Fersit Halt railway station|Fersit]], between Corrour and Tulloch, about 2 miles (3 km) short of the latter.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n[[File:Scotland Corrour Station.jpg|thumb|Corrour station from the south in March 1982, showing the original station house and the footbridge before its removal to Rannoch]]\nSince November 1985, all passenger trains have used the original [[Rail directions#up and down|\u201cdown\u201d]] platform. The \"up\" loop remains and is serviceable but it is no longer used by passenger trains.<ref name=\"RHT\" /> There was originally a footbridge at Corrour station providing an exit to the east side, but it was moved to Rannoch station following the downgrading of the \"up\" loop at Corrour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/event/796121|title=Archaeology Notes - Canmore|website=Canmore.org.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> Passengers now cross the line by a [[Level crossings in the United Kingdom#Barrow crossing|barrow crossing]].<ref name=\"NR\"/>\n\nIn 1998/1999 Corrour Estate replaced the former signalman\u2019s house with a new station house. This included business premises and lodging for their managers and had electric power from a diesel generator.<ref name=\"Canmore 563613\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotlandmag.com/magazine/issue49/12009604.html|title=Magic of the Moor : Scotland Magazine Issue 49|website=Scotlandmag.com|accessdate=8 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116075315/http://www.scotlandmag.com/magazine/issue49/12009604.html|archive-date=16 November 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The station house subsequently had a number of tenants over the years becoming an independent hostel, an SYHA hostel (in addition to the SYHA\u2019s nearby hostel at Loch Ossian), and a restaurant. In 2015, the estate took over the running of the building and after closure for refurbishment reopened it as a bar and restaurant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jimsloire.blogspot.co.uk/2015/06/corrour-station-house-now-closed.html|title=Corrour Station House: now closed|website=Jimsloire.blogspot.co.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn 2012, the red stone chippings on the platform, which [[Network Rail]] acknowledged would be hazardous to wheelchair passengers, were replaced by a hard surface.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.covanburn.com/recent-projects.html|title=Recent Projects At Covanburn Contracts|first=|last=Covanburn.net|website=Covanburn.com|accessdate=8 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116081744/http://www.covanburn.com/recent-projects.html|archive-date=16 November 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Historic Scotland]] [[Listed building|listed]] the disused signalbox (called the \"old watchtower\" by Network Rail) and the adjacent building as [[Listed building#Scotland|Category C]] (the tall boxes at Gorton and Glen Douglas had been demolished).<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB52057|desc=Corrour Station, Waiting Room and Signal Box|cat=C|access-date=12 April 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref> Subsequently, Network Rail, in conjunction with the Corrour Estate and the Railway Heritage Trust, refurbished the signalbox and in 2016 the estate opened three guest rooms in it.<ref name=\"RHT\" />\n\n== Facilities ==\nThe 3-character code for Corrour is CRR.<ref name=\"NR\"/>\n\nCorrour is unstaffed and there are no ticket-issuing facilities, but there is a validator for a \"smartcard\" paperless card-based ticketing system. There are no departure announcements but there is WiFi, a telephone help point, an electronic departure display and a Caledonian Sleeper digital information point. There is a waiting room with bench seats and a cycle rack. The station is lit by electric lights.<ref name=\"NR\"/>\n\n== Services ==\n[[File:Corrour(2).jpg|thumb|left|A train to Mallaig]]\nCorrour station is now passenger-only and is served by regular [[Abellio ScotRail]] passenger trains between [[Glasgow Queen Street railway station|Glasgow Queen Street]] and Fort William/Mallaig. These local services run generally three times a day in each direction, but less frequently on Sundays (twice each way in summer, but just once in winter). In addition, Corrour is served by the [[Caledonian Sleeper]] service between Fort William and London [[Euston railway station|Euston]] via Glasgow Queen Street (Low Level) and [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Edinburgh]] (daily except Saturday nights in each direction). The journey from London to Corrour takes just under twelve hours. The sleeper also conveys seated coaches and can therefore also be used by regular West Highland passengers travelling to or from Glasgow or Edinburgh.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotrail.co.uk/plan-your-journey/timetables-and-routes|title=Scotrail Train Times - Plan your Journey|website=Scotrail.co.uk|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> \nAlthough National Rail state that Corrour is a [[request stop]],<ref name=\"NR\"/> Scotrail's 2019-20 timetable shows it as a compulsory stop.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Abellio ScotRail Ltd |title=West Highlands Train Times |url=https://www.scotrail.co.uk/sites/default/files/assets/download_ct/20238_west_highlands.pdf |website=ScotRail.co.uk |publisher=Abellio ScotRail Ltd |accessdate=22 December 2019 |ref=timetable-201912 |pages=2-3 |format=pdf |date=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIts estimated usage of 14,344 (2018-19) made it the busiest station on the line north of [[Crianlarich railway station|Crianlarich]], apart from Fort William and Mallaig.\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line\n|next     = {{Stnlnk|Tulloch}}\n|previous = {{Stnlnk|Rannoch}}\n|route    = [[Abellio ScotRail]]<br /><small>[[West Highland Line]]</small>\n|col      = {{ScotRail colour}} }}\n{{rail line\n|previous = {{Stnlnk|Rannoch}}\n|next     = {{Stnlnk|Tulloch}}\n|route    = [[Caledonian Sleeper]]<br /><small>[[Caledonian Sleeper|Highland Caledonian Sleeper]]</small>\n|col      = {{CS color}} }}\n{{Historical Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line\n|previous = {{Stnlnk|Rannoch}}\n|next     = {{Stnlnk|Tulloch}}\n|route    = [[North British Railway]]<br /><small>[[West Highland Railway]]</small>\n|col      = {{NBR colour}} |lightcol={{NBR light}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n{{clear left}}\n\n== Signalling ==\n[[File:Corrour railway station.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Corrour station from the north, in April 2004]]\nThe [[signal box]], which had 13 levers, was situated to the south of the [[island platform]]. From the time of its opening in 1894, the West Highland Railway was worked throughout by the electric [[Token (railway signalling)|token system]]. The [[Railway semaphore signal|semaphore signals]] were removed in November 1985 in preparation for the introduction of [[Radio Electronic Token Block]] (RETB). At the same time, the loop [[points (rail)|points]] came under the control of [[Ground frame|ground frames]]. The RETB system was commissioned by [[British Rail]] between {{Stnlnk|Upper Tyndrum}} and [[Fort William Junction]] on 29 May 1988. This resulted in the closure of Corrour [[Railway signalling|signal]] box and others on that part of the route. The RETB is controlled from a Signalling Centre at [[Banavie railway station]].{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n== Cultural references ==\n\nThe station, and the nearby mountain [[Leum Uilleim]], gained fame when they were featured in a scene from the film ''[[Trainspotting (film)|Trainspotting]]''. It also appeared in the fourth episode of the 2010 [[BBC]] series ''[[Secret Britain]]''. The station also featured in the [[Young Guns (band)|Young Guns]] video for the single \"Weight of the World\". The station is the primary location in Jos Stelling's film ''[[De Wisselwachter]]''.  It was also visited by [[Paul Merton]] in Episode 3 of his [[Channel 4]] documentary series ''Paul Merton's Secret Stations''.<ref>[http://www.channel4.com/info/press/programme-information/paul-mertons-secret-stations] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160530232046/http://www.channel4.com/info/press/programme-information/paul-mertons-secret-stations |date=30 May 2016 }} ''Channel 4 Programme Information'' website; Retrieved 16 May 2016</ref>\n\nThe route south from Corrour across the Moor of Rannoch to Rannoch Station itself was used as a filming location in the ''Harry Potter'' films where a [[Death Eater]] was seen to stand between the rails with an outstretched arm, to bring the approaching Hogwarts Express to a stand for the train to be inspected. Warner Brothers spent a couple of days with equipment based at Rannoch to facilitate the filming sequences.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Brailsford |editor-first=Martyn |title=Railway Track Diagrams 1: Scotland & Isle of Man |edition=6th |date=December 2017 |origyear=1987 |publisher=Trackmaps |location=Frome |isbn=978-0-9549866-9-8 |ref=harv }}\n* {{Butt-Stations}}\n* {{Jowett-Atlas}}\n* {{Jowett-Nationalised}}\n* McGregor, John A., ''All Stations to Mallaig'', D. Bradford Barton Ltd, 1st edition, 1982. {{ISBN|0-85153-426-0}}\n* ''Mountain Moor and Loch: on the Route of the West Highland Railway'', Sir Joseph Causton & Sons, 1st edition, 1894\n* Thomas, John, ''The West Highland Railway'', David St John Thomas, 3rd edition, 1992, {{ISBN|0-946537-22-4}}\n* {{Quail-1}}\n* [http://www.scotlandthemovie.com/movies/rantrain.html Scotland: the Movie Location Guide \u2013 Trainspotting, Rannoch Moor] Information on the station as it appears in \"Trainspotting\".\n* [https://www.railscot.co.uk/West_Highland_Railway/index.php] Further details on the station.\n* [http://www.hiddeneurope.co.uk/article_info.php?articles_id=249 Hidden Europe magazine] \u2013 an article about Corrour from ''Hidden Europe'' magazine\n* Article on the station by Ian Futers, four pages including track plan, photos, and description in [https://archive.is/20070503043613/http://www.peco-uk.com/Publications/RailwayM_this.htm ''Railway Modeller''] magazine for April 2008\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p53ECuJFtD0 Annotated video of Corrour station and restaurant]\n* {{Commonscat-inline|Corrour railway station}}\n\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Highland (council area)]]\n[[Category:Former North British Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1894]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by Abellio ScotRail]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by Caledonian Sleeper]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Great Britain without road access]]\n[[Category:Railway request stops in Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Listed railway stations in Scotland]]\n[[Category:1894 establishments in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Jonathan Barrett", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCultural references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corrour_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Nafsika Antypas", "text_new": "{{db-bio}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name= Nafsika Antypas\n| birth_place = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]\n| occupation = Television host\n| television = ''[[Plant-Based by Nafsika]]''\n}}\n'''Nafsika Antypas''' is a Canadian [[infomercial]] host and [[vegan]].\n\n==Personal life==\nNafsika Antypas was born and raised in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]\n\n==Veganism==\nIn 2016 Antypas became the host of an [[infomercial]] called ''[[Plant-Based by Nafsika]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vegnews.com/2016/5/worlds-first-vegan-lifestyle-series-to-debut-on-aandampe|title=World\u2019s First Vegan Lifestyle Series to Debut on A&E|publisher=Vegan News}}</ref> Topics for the show included cooking demonstrations, interviews with doctors and nutritionists, celebrity guests,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.peta.org/living/entertainment/first-vegan-lifestyle-show-plant-based-by-nafsika/|title=First-Ever Vegan Lifestyle Show Coming to a TV Near You - PETA|publisher=PETA}}</ref> and \u201ccruelty free\u201d fashion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.plantbasednews.org/post/4-incredible-facts-about-vegan-cable-tv-show-plant-based-by-nafsika|title=4 Incredible Facts About Vegan Cable TV Show \u2018Plant Based by Nafsika\u2019|publisher=}}</ref> \n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Antypas, Nafsika}}\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Veganism activists]]\n[[Category:Canadian television hosts]]\n[[Category:Canadian food industry businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name= Nafsika Antypas\n| birth_place = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]\n| occupation = Television host\n| television = ''[[Plant-Based by Nafsika]]''\n}}\n'''Nafsika Antypas''' is a Canadian television host and [[veganism]] advocate.\n\n==Personal life==\nNafsika Antypas was born and raised in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], and began her professional career with her father\u2019s Mediterranean food import company Pilaros.<ref name=Raven>{{cite web|url=https://vegnews.com/2017/5/a-sneak-preview-of-plant-based-by-nafsikas-second-season|title=A Sneak Preview of Plant-Based by Nafsika\u2019s Second Season|publisher=Vegan News}}</ref> She currently serves as the company\u2019s marketing director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ktep.org/post/act-radio-nafsika-antypas|title=ACT RADIO: Nafsika Antypas|publisher=[[KTEP|NPR]]}}</ref>\n\n==Veganism==\nNafsika Antypas\u2019 first vegan project was People Against Violence, a non-profit organization she founded in 2014.<ref name=Raven /> She then founded The Struggling Vegan, a vegan consultation and advocacy firm,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.plantbasednews.org/post/revealed-top-100-most-influential-vegans-of-2017|title=REVEALED: Top 100 Most Influential Vegans Of 2017|publisher=Plant Based News}}</ref> in 2015.<ref name=Flink /> \nIn 2016 Antypas became the host for the world\u2019s first Vegan lifestyle television show, ''[[Plant-Based by Nafsika]]'' on the [[FYI (U.S. TV network)|A&E's FYI Network]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vegnews.com/2016/5/worlds-first-vegan-lifestyle-series-to-debut-on-aandampe|title=World\u2019s First Vegan Lifestyle Series to Debut on A&E|publisher=Vegan News}}</ref> Topics for the show included cooking demonstrations, interviews with doctors and nutritionists, celebrity guests,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.peta.org/living/entertainment/first-vegan-lifestyle-show-plant-based-by-nafsika/|title=First-Ever Vegan Lifestyle Show Coming to a TV Near You - PETA|publisher=PETA}}</ref> and \u201ccruelty free\u201d fashion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.plantbasednews.org/post/4-incredible-facts-about-vegan-cable-tv-show-plant-based-by-nafsika|title=4 Incredible Facts About Vegan Cable TV Show \u2018Plant Based by Nafsika\u2019|publisher=}}</ref> The second season of the show aired in 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://streetregister.com/2017/07/24/big-exposure-coming-for-terra-tech-corp-otcmktstrtc-subsidiary/|title=Big Exposure Coming for Terra Tech Corp (OTCMKTS:TRTC) Subsidiary |publisher=Street Register|first=Michael|last=Luke|website=streetregister.com}}</ref> and the third season aired in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livekindly.co/natalie-portman-pitches-vegan-cooking-show-during-premiere-of-eating-animals/|title=Natalie Portman Says She Wants to Launch Her Own Vegan Cooking Show|date=18 June 2018|publisher=Live Kindly}}</ref> \nIn 2017 Antypas gained her certification as a health and lifestyle coach.<ref name=Flink>{{cite web|url=https://www.livekindly.co/3rd-season-of-hit-vegan-lifestyle-tv-show-plant-based-by-nafsika-to-air-on-ae/|title=Hit Vegan Lifestyle TV Show to Launch 3rd Season on A&E|date=23 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref> She has also contributed articles to publications including ''[[The Oakland Press]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theoaklandpress.com/lifestyles/health/being-vegan-is-easier-than-ever/article_b7695256-a8fb-5d91-a002-7e2e1b4a1b32.html|title=Being vegan is easier than ever|first=Nafsika Antypas For Digital First|last=Media|publisher=The Oakland Press}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Antypas, Nafsika}}\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Veganism activists]]\n[[Category:Canadian television hosts]]\n[[Category:Canadian food industry businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "PlantFaced", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(removed non-notable vanity info)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nafsika_Antypas"}
{"title_page": "Decentralized application", "text_new": "{{short description|Type of computer application}}\n{{about|trustless decentralized applications|other types of decentralized applications|Distributed computing}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|date=June 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n}}\nA '''decentralized application''' ('''DApp'''<ref>{{Cite web|title=CVC Money Transmission Services Provided Through Decentralized Applications (DApps)|url=https://www.fincen.gov/sites/default/files/2019-05/FinCEN%20CVC%20Guidance%20FINAL.pdf|website=FinCEN|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref>, '''dApp''', '''Dapp''', or '''dapp''') is a computer [[application software|application]] that runs on a [[distributed computing]] system. DApps have been popularized by [[Distributed ledger|distributed ledger technologies]] (DLT) such as the [[Ethereum]] [[Blockchain]], where DApps are often referred to as [[smart contract]]s.\n\nDApps can be browsed on marketplaces such as State of the DApps, Dapp.com, Holdex, DAppRadar and CoinGecko.\n\n==Characteristics==\nDApps have their backend code running on a decentralized peer-to-peer network, as opposed to typical applications where the backend code is running on centralized servers. A DApp can have frontend code and user interfaces written in any language that can make calls to its backend. Furthermore, its frontend can be hosted on decentralized storage such as Swarm or IPFS.\n\nDApps are typically open source, decentralized, incentivized through providing tokens to those who validate the DApp, and in compliance with a specific protocol agreed upon within the community.\n\n==Deployment==\nDApps may run on top of distributed computing systems such as [[Ethereum]] or [[Bitcoin]]. Decentralized applications are stored on and executed by a [[Blockchain|blockchain system]]. Steem created a well-established ecosystem that leads to the widespread adoption of DApp development.\nThere are large number of DApps that are serving well in various industries. Examples are Steem Monsters, dMania, Steemblr, Musing and SteemHunt etc.\n\n==Adoption==\nThere have been criticisms of DApps surrounding their inaccessibility to the average user. Many DApps struggle to attract users, particularly in their founding stages, and even those that attract widespread initial popularity struggle to retain it. A notable example was the DApp [[CryptoKitties]], which crashed the [[Ethereum]] network at the height of its popularity <ref>https://techcrunch.com/2017/12/03/people-have-spent-over-1m-buying-virtual-cats-on-the-ethereum-blockchain/</ref>. CryptoKitties and another similar gaming-based DApp, Dice Games, have failed to attract similar traction since.<ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/cryptokitties-and-dice-games-fail-to-lure-users-to-dapps-11559122201</ref>\n\nHowever, there remains optimism in the cryptography community that DApps will achieve better adoption rates in coming years. A report by UK-based market intelligence Juniper Research stated that the DApps most likely to first gain mass adoption would deal with verifying [[Digital identity certificate|digital identities]] or tracking products through supply chains.\n\n== Examples ==\n<!-- Examples should be notable, ie. with a Wikipedia entry -->\n\n*[[Cryptokitties]] -  Game based on the Ethereum. It slowed Ethereum down due to insufficient transaction processing and exposed the scaling limitations of public blockchains.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-04/cryptokitties-quickly-becomes-most-widely-used-ethereum-app|title=CryptoKitties Mania Overwhelms Ethereum Network's Processing|last=Kharif|first=Olga|date=2017-12-05|work=Bloomberg|access-date=2018-08-23}}</ref>\n\n* [[Augur (software)|Augur]]<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite news |last1=Leising |first1=Matthew |title=As Crypto Meets Prediction Markets, Regulators Take Notice |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-07-26/as-crypto-meets-prediction-markets-u-s-regulators-take-notice |work=Bloomberg |date=July 26, 2018}}</ref> - [[prediction market]] platform\n\n*[[Blockstack]] - a platform for developing decentralized applications.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/sep/08/decentralisation-next-big-step-for-the-world-wide-web-dweb-data-internet-censorship-brewster-kahle|title=Decentralisation: the next big step for the world wide web|last=Corbyn|first=Zo\u00eb|date=2018-09-08|work=The Observer|access-date=2019-10-06|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref>\n\n*[[Freelance]] - platform on smart contract.\n*[https://8coins.org 8coins] - dApp builder for creating Ethereum and Tron dApps without coding.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Cryptocurrencies}}\n\n[[Category:Blockchains]]\n[[Category:Cryptocurrencies]]\n[[Category:Decentralization]]\n[[Category:Distributed computing]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Type of computer application}}\n{{about|trustless decentralized applications|other types of decentralized applications|Distributed computing}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|date=June 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n}}\nA '''decentralized application''' ('''DApp'''<ref>{{Cite web|title=CVC Money Transmission Services Provided Through Decentralized Applications (DApps)|url=https://www.fincen.gov/sites/default/files/2019-05/FinCEN%20CVC%20Guidance%20FINAL.pdf|website=FinCEN|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref>, '''dApp''', '''Dapp''', or '''dapp''') is a computer [[application software|application]] that runs on a [[distributed computing]] system. DApps have been popularized by [[Distributed ledger|distributed ledger technologies]] (DLT) such as the [[Ethereum]] [[Blockchain]], where DApps are often referred to as [[smart contract]]s.\n\nDApps can be browsed on marketplaces such as State of the DApps, Dapp.com, Holdex, DAppRadar and CoinGecko.\n\n==Characteristics==\nDApps have their backend code running on a decentralized peer-to-peer network, as opposed to typical applications where the backend code is running on centralized servers. A DApp can have frontend code and user interfaces written in any language that can make calls to its backend. Furthermore, its frontend can be hosted on decentralized storage such as Swarm or IPFS.\n\nDApps are typically open source, decentralized, incentivized through providing tokens to those who validate the DApp, and in compliance with a specific protocol agreed upon within the community.\n\n==Deployment==\nDApps may run on top of distributed computing systems such as [[Ethereum]] or [[Bitcoin]]. Decentralized applications are stored on and executed by a [[Blockchain|blockchain system]]. Steem created a well-established ecosystem that leads to the widespread adoption of DApp development.\nThere are large number of DApps that are serving well in various industries. Examples are Steem Monsters, dMania, Steemblr, Musing and SteemHunt etc.\n\n==Adoption==\nThere have been criticisms of DApps surrounding their inaccessibility to the average user. Many DApps struggle to attract users, particularly in their founding stages, and even those that attract widespread initial popularity struggle to retain it. A notable example was the DApp [[CryptoKitties]], which crashed the [[Ethereum]] network at the height of its popularity <ref>https://techcrunch.com/2017/12/03/people-have-spent-over-1m-buying-virtual-cats-on-the-ethereum-blockchain/</ref>. CryptoKitties and another similar gaming-based DApp, Dice Games, have failed to attract similar traction since.<ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/cryptokitties-and-dice-games-fail-to-lure-users-to-dapps-11559122201</ref>\n\nHowever, there remains optimism in the cryptography community that DApps will achieve better adoption rates in coming years. A report by UK-based market intelligence Juniper Research stated that the DApps most likely to first gain mass adoption would deal with verifying [[Digital identity certificate|digital identities]] or tracking products through supply chains.\n\n== Examples ==\n<!-- Examples should be notable, ie. with a Wikipedia entry -->\n\n*[[Cryptokitties]] -  Game based on the Ethereum. It slowed Ethereum down due to insufficient transaction processing and exposed the scaling limitations of public blockchains.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-04/cryptokitties-quickly-becomes-most-widely-used-ethereum-app|title=CryptoKitties Mania Overwhelms Ethereum Network's Processing|last=Kharif|first=Olga|date=2017-12-05|work=Bloomberg|access-date=2018-08-23}}</ref>\n\n* [[Augur (software)|Augur]]<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite news |last1=Leising |first1=Matthew |title=As Crypto Meets Prediction Markets, Regulators Take Notice |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-07-26/as-crypto-meets-prediction-markets-u-s-regulators-take-notice |work=Bloomberg |date=July 26, 2018}}</ref> - [[prediction market]] platform\n\n*[[Blockstack]] - a platform for developing decentralized applications.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/sep/08/decentralisation-next-big-step-for-the-world-wide-web-dweb-data-internet-censorship-brewster-kahle|title=Decentralisation: the next big step for the world wide web|last=Corbyn|first=Zo\u00eb|date=2018-09-08|work=The Observer|access-date=2019-10-06|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref>\n\n*[[Freelance]] - platform on smart contract.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Cryptocurrencies}}\n\n[[Category:Blockchains]]\n[[Category:Cryptocurrencies]]\n[[Category:Decentralization]]\n[[Category:Distributed computing]]\n", "name_user": "27.68.66.119", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExamples)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decentralized_application"}
{"title_page": "Pushyamitra Shunga", "text_new": "{{for|the 5th century CE tribe|Pushyamitras}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| succession          = [[Shunga Empire|Shunga Emperor]]\n| image               = [[File:Bharhut Sunga individual.jpg|200px]]\n| caption             = Man on a relief, [[Bharhut]], Sunga period, 2nd century BCE.\n| reign               = {{circa|185|149 BCE}}\n| religion            = [[Brahmanism]]\n| predecessor         = [[Brihadratha Maurya]]\n| successor           = [[Agnimitra]]\n| spouse              = \n| issue               = [[Agnimitra]]\n| dynasty             = [[Shunga Empire|Shunga]]\n| father              = \n| mother              = \n| birth_date          = \n| birth_place         = \n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| date of burial      = \n| place of burial     = \n}}\n\n'''Pushyamitra Shunga''' ([[IAST]]: {{IAST|Pu\u1e63yamitra \u015au\u1e45ga}}) ({{circa|185|149 BCE}}) was the founder and first ruler of the [[Shunga Empire]] in [[East India]]. He was a follower of Persian Zoroastrian [[Historical Vedic religion|Brahmanism]].\n\nPushyamitra was originally a ''Senapati'' \"General\" of the [[Maurya Empire]]. In 185 BCE he assassinated the last Mauryan Emperor, [[Brihadratha Maurya]], during an army review, and proclaimed himself emperor. \n\nPushyamitra is recorded to have performed numerous [[Ashvamedha]] campaigns to legitimize his right to rule.\n\nInscriptions of the Shungas have been found as far as the [[Ayodhya]] (the [[Dhanadeva-Ayodhya inscription]]), and the ''[[Divyavadana]]'' mentions that he sent an army to persecute Buddhist monks as far as [[Sagala|Sakala]] ([[Sialkot]]) in the [[Punjab region]] in the northwest.\n\nThe Buddhist texts state that Pushyamitra cruelly persecuted the Buddhists, although some modern scholars have expressed skepticism about these claims.\n\n== Ancestry ==\n[[File:I17 1karshapana Sunga MACW4325 1ar (8485402873).jpg|thumb|300px|A silver coin of 1 [[karshapana]] of King Pushyamitra Sunga (185-149 BC) of the Sunga dynasty (185-73 BC), workshop of Vidisa (?). ''Obv:'' 5 symbols including a sun ''Rev:'' 2 symbols.]]\n[[File:SungaCoin.JPG|thumb|300px|Bronze coin of the Shunga period, Eastern India. 2nd\u20131st century BCE.]]\nPushyamitra Shunga was the hereditary ruler of [[Vidisha]]. It was incorporated into the Maurya Empire uptil his led [[coup d'\u00e9tat]].\n\nSeveral sources suggest that Pushyamitra was a [[Brahmin]] [[warrior]] and the 16th century Buddhist scholar [[Taranatha]] explicitly calls him a Brahmin king.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=29}} However, the various sources offer differing suggestions about which Brahmin [[gotra]] (clan) Pushyamitra belonged to. A [[Purana|Puranic]] manuscript mentions persons who were born of \"Shunga, a descendant of [[Bharadvaja]], by a woman married in the family of Kata, a descendant of [[Vishvamitra]]\". Based on this, [[K. P. Jayaswal]] theorized that Shunga was a [[Brahmin]] with two gotras (''dwaimushyayana'' or ''dvigotra''): his family traced their ancestry to both Bharadvaja and Vishvamitra lineages.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|pp=28-29}} The ''Pravara Kanda'' of the ''[[Apastamba]]'' mentions a \"Shunga-Shaishiri\" gotra. J. C. Ghosh theorized that the Shunga family derived from the Shunga of the Bharadvaja gotra, and the Shaishiri of the Vishvamitra gotra (Kata group).{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=30}}<ref>''Ghosh, J.C.,\"The Dynastic-Name of the Kings of the Pushyamitra Family,\" J.B.O.R.S, Vol. XXXIII, 1937, p.360''</ref>\n\nHowever, the ''[[Matsya Purana]]'' mentions the \"Shunga-Shaishiri\" ''dwaimushyayana'' gotra (named \"Shaunga-Shaishireya\" here) as a combination of the Bharadvaja and [[Kashyapa]] (not Vishvamitra) gotras. The ''[[Harivamsa]]'' mentions a [[dvija|twice-born]] general of the [[Kashyapa]] gotra who performed the [[Ashvamedha]] sacrifice. Some scholars such as Jayaswal identify this general with Pushyamitra. The ''[[Malavikagnimitra]]'' describes Pushyamitra as a \"Baimbaki\". [[Hem Chandra Raychaudhuri|H. C. Raychaudhuri]], who read this term as \"Baimbika\", identified it with Baimbakayah of the [[Baudhayana Shrauta Sutra]], who was of the Kashyapa gotra (although other scholars believe that the term \"Baimbaki\" signifies descent from a person named Bimba, or refers to a heroic lover in general).{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|pp=29-30}} Bela Lahiri theorizes that the constituents of a ''dwaimushyayana'' gotra may have differed during different periods, and Pushyamitra may have belonged to one of these gotras.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=33}}\n\nAccording to the Puranas, Pushyamitra became the king after killing his master [[Brihadratha]], the last Mauryan king.{{sfn|Thapar|2013|p=296}} However, the Buddhist text ''[[Divyavadana]]'' names Pushyamitra as the last Mauryan king.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=29}} This text appears to have confused Brihadratha with Pushyamitra.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=30}}\n\nH. C. Raychaudhuri theorized that the name \"Shunga\" is derived from the Sanskrit word for the fig tree.<ref>''Raychaudhari Hemchandra, \"Tha Audvijja Senani of the Harivansa?\", Indian culture, Vol. IV, 1938, P. 360-365''</ref>\n\n== Alleged persecution of Buddhists ==\n=== Buddhist accounts ===\n[[File:Sunga horseman Bharhut.jpg|thumb|Sunga horseman, Bharhut.]]\nBuddhist texts state that Pushyamitra cruelly persecuted the Buddhists. The earliest source to mention this is the 2nd Century CE text ''[[Ashokavadana]]'' (a part of ''[[Divyavadana]]''). According to this account, Pushyamitra (described as the last Mauryan king) wanted to be famous. His ministers advised him that as long as Buddhism remained the dominant faith, he would never be as famous as his ancestor [[Ashoka]], who had commissioned 84,000 [[stupa]]s. One advisor told him that he could become famous by destroying Buddhism. Pushyamitra then tried to destroy the [[Kukkutarama]] monastery, but it was saved by a miracle. He then proceeded to [[Sagala|Shakala]] in the north-west, where he offered a prize of one hundred ''dinara''s (gold coins) for every head of a Buddhist monk brought to him. Next, he proceeded to the Koshthaka kingdom, where a Buddhist [[yaksha]] named Damshtranivasin killed him and his army with help of another yaksha named Krimisha.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|pp=95-96}}{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=33}}\n\n{{quote|... Pushyamitra equipped a fourfold army, and intending to destroy the Buddhist religion, he went to the [[Kukkutarama]] (in [[Pataliputra]]). ... Pushyamitra therefore destroyed the [[sangharama]], killed the monks there, and departed. ... After some time, he arrived in [[Sagala|Sakala]], and proclaimed that he would give a ... reward to whoever brought him the head of a Buddhist monk.{{sf|Strong|1989|p=293}}}}\n\n''Vibhasa'', another 2nd century text, states that Pushyamitra burned Buddhist scriptures, killed Buddhist monks, and destroyed 500 monasteries in and around [[Kashmir]]. In this campaign, he was supported by yakshas, ''kumbhanda''s, and other demons. However, when he reached the [[Bodhi tree]], the deity of that tree took the form of a beautiful woman and killed him.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=96}} ''Shariputrapariprichha'', translated into Chinese between 317 and 420 CE also mentions this legend, but this particular version is more detailed, and describes eastern India (not Kashmir) as the center of Pushyamitra's anti-Buddhist campaign.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=96}}\n\nThe medieval-era ''Arya-Manjushri-Mula-Kalpa'' mentions a wicked and foolish king named Gomimukhya (\"cattle-faced\"), or Gomishanda (\"Gomin, the bull\"), who seized the territory from the east to Kashmir, destroying monasteries and killing monks. Ultimately, he and his officers were killed in the north by falling mountain rocks.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=96}}{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=33-34}} This king is identified with Pushyamitra by some scholars.<ref>{{cite book |first=Jayantanuja |last=Bandyopadhyaya |title=Class and Religion in Ancient India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gwUF11NRyT4C&pg=PA209 |year=2007 |publisher=Anthem |isbn=978-1-84331-332-8 |page=209 }}</ref>\n\nThe 16th-century Tibetan Buddhist historian [[Taranatha]] also states that Pushyamitra and his allies killed Buddhist monks and destroyed monasteries from ''madhyadesha'' (midland) to [[Jalandhar]]a. These activities wiped out the Buddhist doctrine from the north, within five years.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=96}}\n\n=== Authenticity of Buddhist claims ===\n[[File:Procession on Elephants. Bharhut, c. 100 BC. Indian Museum, Calcutta ei05-19.jpg|thumb|Men riding elephants. [[Bharhut]], Sunga period.]]\nBased on Buddhist tradition, some scholars believe that Pushyamitra was indeed a persecutor of the Buddhist faith. However, others believe that Buddhist scholars were biased against Pushyamitra, because he did not patronize them.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|pp=34-35}}\n\n[[Vincent Arthur Smith|V. A. Smith]] and H. P. Shastri believed that Pushyamitra's rebellion against the Maurya dynasty was a Brahminical reaction to the rise of Buddhism.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=34}} According to archaeologist [[John Marshall (archaeologist)|John Marshall]], there is evidence of some damage to Buddhist establishments at [[Takshashila]] around the time of Shunga rule. He also theorized that the [[Sanchi Stupa|Sanchi stupa]] was vandalized in 2nd century BCE (that is, during Pushyamitra's reign), before being rebuilt on a larger scale.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|pp=96-97}} G. R. Sharma, who excavated the Buddhist ruins at [[Kosambi|Kaushambi]], suggested that the destruction of the local monastery might have happened during the reign of Pushyamitra Shunga. P. K. Mishra believes that the damage to the [[Deur Kothar]] stupa is also datable to Pushyamitra's period.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=97}} H. C. Raychaudhari pointed out that Buddhist monuments were constructed at [[Bharhut]] during the Shunga rule.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=34}} However, according to N. N. Ghosh, these were constructed during the reign of later Shunga rulers, not Pushyamitra's period.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=97}}\n\nH. Bhattacharya theorized that Pushyamitra might have persecuted Buddhists for political, rather than religious, reasons: the politically active Buddhists probably supported the [[Indo-Greek Kingdom|Indo-Greek]] rivals of Pushyamitra, which might have prompted him to persecute them.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=100}} The ''Ashokavadana'' states that Pushyamitra declared a reward for killing Buddhist monks in [[Sagala|Shakala]] (present-day Sialkot), which was located near the Indo-Greek frontiers. According to K. P. Jayaswal, this further highlights a political motivation behind his alleged persecution of Buddhists.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|pp=99-100}}\n\nMany other scholars have expressed skepticism about the Buddhist claims of persecution by Pushyamitra. [[\u00c9tienne Lamotte]] points out that the Buddhist legends are not consistent about the location of Pushyamitra's anti-Buddhist campaign and his death.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=98}} The ''Ashokavadana'' claims that Pushyamitra offered ''dinara''s as a reward for killing Buddhist monks, but the ''dinara'' did not come into circulation in India before the 1st century CE. ''Ashokavadana'' also claims that Ashoka persecuted ''Nirgrantha''s ([[Ajivika]]s), which is an obvious fabrication, considering that Ashoka's edicts express tolerance towards all religious sects.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=99}} The Sri Lankan Buddhist text ''[[Mahavamsa]]'' suggests that several monasteries existed in present-day Bihar, Awadh and Malwa at the time Pushyamitra's contemporary [[Dutthagamani]] ruled in Lanka. This suggests that these monasteries survived Pushyamitra Shunga's reign.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=100}}\n\nH. C. Raychaudhury argued that Pushyamitra's overthrow of the Mauryans cannot be considered as a Brahmin uprising against Buddhist rule, as Brahmins did not suffer during the Mauryan rule: Ashoka's edicts mention the Brahmins before [[Shramana]]s, and the appointment of a Brahmin general (Pushyamitra) shows that the Brahmins were honoured at the Mauryan court.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=34}} The fact that the ''Ashokavadana'' mentions Pushyamitra as a Mauryan further erodes its historical credibility, and weakens the hypothesis that he persecuted Buddhists because he was a Brahmin.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=99}} Raychaudhury also aruged that according to ''[[Malavikagnimitra]]'', a Buddhist nun named Bhagavati Kaushiki attended Pushyamitra's court, which indicates that they did not persecute Buddhists. However, Shankar Goyal states that there is no evidence of Kaushiki being a Buddhist nun.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rxpuAAAAMAAJ |title=Aspects of ancient Indian history and historiography |author=Shankar Goyal |publisher=Harman |year=1993 |isbn=9788185151694 |page=30 }}</ref> [[Romila Thapar]] writes that the lack of concrete archaeological evidence casts doubt on the claims of Buddhist persecution by Pushyamitra.<ref>A\u015boka and the Decline of the Mauryas by Romila Thapar, Oxford University Press, 1960 P200</ref>\n\nIt is possible that the Buddhist influence at the Mauryan court declined during Pushyamitra's reign, and the Buddhist monasteries and other institutions stopped receiving royal patronage. This change might have led to discontent among the Buddhists, resulting in exaggerated accounts of persecution.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|pp=99-100}}\n\n[[Michael Witzel]] states that ''[[Manu Smriti|Manudharma]]'', which emphasizes the role of orthodox faith in state-craft and society, was first compiled under Pushyamitra's rule. According to Kaushik Roy, it was a Brahmanical reaction to the rise of Buddhism and Jainism.<ref name=\"roy\">Roy, Kaushik (2012). Hinduism and the Ethics of Warfare in South Asia: From Antiquity to the Present, p.109-118. Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|9781107017368}}</ref>\n\n== Succession of the throne ==\nPushyamitra Shunga was succeeded in 148 BCE by his son [[Agnimitra]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Ancient Indian History and Civilization |first=Sailendra Nath  |last=Sen |publisher=New Age International, 1999 |year=1999 |isbn=978-8-12241-198-0 |page=170 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wk4_ICH_g1EC&pg=PA170}}</ref>\n\n== In literature ==\nPushyamitra Shunga's history is recorded in the [[Harshacharita]] authored by [[B\u0101\u1e47abha\u1e6d\u1e6da]].\n\nAccording to ''Vicarasreni'' of [[Merutunga]], Pushyamitra or Pushpamitra got his throne in 204 BC.{{sfn|Jain|1991|p=85}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [[History of Buddhism]]\n* [[Indo-Greeks]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{ref begin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Jain |first=Kailash Chand |title=Lord Mah\u0101v\u012bra and His Times |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8-TxcO9dfrcC |date=1991 |publisher=[[Motilal Banarsidass]] | isbn=978-81-208-0805-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Simmons|first1=Caleb|last2=Sarao|first2=K. T. S.|editor1-last=Danver|editor1-first=Steven L.|title=Popular Controversies in World History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=slVobUjdzGMC |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-59884-078-0 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vdu1AAAAIAAJ |title=Indigenous states of northern India, circa 200 B.C. to 320 A.D. |first=Bela |last=Lahiri |publisher=University of Calcutta |year=1974 |page=31 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Strong|first1=John S.|authorlink = John S. Strong|title=The Legend of King A\u015boka : a study and translation of the A\u015bok\u0101vad\u0101na|date=1989|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton|isbn=0-691-01459-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kp9uaQTQ8h8C&pg=PA232|ref=harv}}\n* {{citation |last=Thapar |first=Romila |author-link=Romila Thapar |title=The Past Before Us|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aei9AAAAQBAJ |year=2013 |publisher=[[Harvard University Press]] |isbn=978-0-674-72651-2 }}\n{{ref end}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Shunga Empire|King of Shunga Dynasty]]\n| years = 185\u2013149 BCE\n| before = [[Mauryan Dynasty]]''<br /> '''[[Brihadratha Maurya]]''\n| after = [[Agnimitra]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shunga, Pushyamitra}}\n[[Category:2nd-century BC Indian monarchs]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:180s BC births]]\n[[Category:140s BC deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the 5th century CE tribe|Pushyamitras}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| succession          = [[Shunga Empire|Shunga Emperor]]\n| image               = [[File:Bharhut Sunga individual.jpg|200px]]\n| caption             = Man on a relief, [[Bharhut]], Sunga period, 2nd century BCE.\n| reign               = {{circa|185|149 BCE}}\n| religion            = [[Brahmanism]]\n| predecessor         = [[Brihadratha Maurya]]\n| successor           = [[Agnimitra]]\n| spouse              = \n| issue               = [[Agnimitra]]\n| dynasty             = [[Shunga Empire|Shunga]]\n| father              = \n| mother              = \n| birth_date          = \n| birth_place         = \n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| date of burial      = \n| place of burial     = \n}}\n\n'''Pushyamitra Shunga''' ([[IAST]]: {{IAST|Pu\u1e63yamitra \u015au\u1e45ga}}) ({{circa|185|149 BCE}}) was the founder and first ruler of the [[Shunga Empire]] in [[East India]]. He was a follower of [[Historical Vedic religion|Brahmanism]].\n\nPushyamitra was originally a ''Senapati'' \"General\" of the [[Maurya Empire]]. In 185 BCE he assassinated the last Mauryan Emperor, [[Brihadratha Maurya]], during an army review, and proclaimed himself emperor. \n\nPushyamitra is recorded to have performed numerous [[Ashvamedha]] campaigns to legitimize his right to rule.\n\nInscriptions of the Shungas have been found as far as the [[Ayodhya]] (the [[Dhanadeva-Ayodhya inscription]]), and the ''[[Divyavadana]]'' mentions that he sent an army to persecute Buddhist monks as far as [[Sagala|Sakala]] ([[Sialkot]]) in the [[Punjab region]] in the northwest.\n\nThe Buddhist texts state that Pushyamitra cruelly persecuted the Buddhists, although some modern scholars have expressed skepticism about these claims.\n\n== Ancestry ==\n[[File:I17 1karshapana Sunga MACW4325 1ar (8485402873).jpg|thumb|300px|A silver coin of 1 [[karshapana]] of King Pushyamitra Sunga (185-149 BC) of the Sunga dynasty (185-73 BC), workshop of Vidisa (?). ''Obv:'' 5 symbols including a sun ''Rev:'' 2 symbols.]]\n[[File:SungaCoin.JPG|thumb|300px|Bronze coin of the Shunga period, Eastern India. 2nd\u20131st century BCE.]]\nPushyamitra Shunga was the hereditary ruler of [[Vidisha]]. It was incorporated into the Maurya Empire uptil his led [[coup d'\u00e9tat]].\n\nSeveral sources suggest that Pushyamitra was a [[Brahmin]] [[warrior]] and the 16th century Buddhist scholar [[Taranatha]] explicitly calls him a Brahmin king.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=29}} However, the various sources offer differing suggestions about which Brahmin [[gotra]] (clan) Pushyamitra belonged to. A [[Purana|Puranic]] manuscript mentions persons who were born of \"Shunga, a descendant of [[Bharadvaja]], by a woman married in the family of Kata, a descendant of [[Vishvamitra]]\". Based on this, [[K. P. Jayaswal]] theorized that Shunga was a [[Brahmin]] with two gotras (''dwaimushyayana'' or ''dvigotra''): his family traced their ancestry to both Bharadvaja and Vishvamitra lineages.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|pp=28-29}} The ''Pravara Kanda'' of the ''[[Apastamba]]'' mentions a \"Shunga-Shaishiri\" gotra. J. C. Ghosh theorized that the Shunga family derived from the Shunga of the Bharadvaja gotra, and the Shaishiri of the Vishvamitra gotra (Kata group).{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=30}}<ref>''Ghosh, J.C.,\"The Dynastic-Name of the Kings of the Pushyamitra Family,\" J.B.O.R.S, Vol. XXXIII, 1937, p.360''</ref>\n\nHowever, the ''[[Matsya Purana]]'' mentions the \"Shunga-Shaishiri\" ''dwaimushyayana'' gotra (named \"Shaunga-Shaishireya\" here) as a combination of the Bharadvaja and [[Kashyapa]] (not Vishvamitra) gotras. The ''[[Harivamsa]]'' mentions a [[dvija|twice-born]] general of the [[Kashyapa]] gotra who performed the [[Ashvamedha]] sacrifice. Some scholars such as Jayaswal identify this general with Pushyamitra. The ''[[Malavikagnimitra]]'' describes Pushyamitra as a \"Baimbaki\". [[Hem Chandra Raychaudhuri|H. C. Raychaudhuri]], who read this term as \"Baimbika\", identified it with Baimbakayah of the [[Baudhayana Shrauta Sutra]], who was of the Kashyapa gotra (although other scholars believe that the term \"Baimbaki\" signifies descent from a person named Bimba, or refers to a heroic lover in general).{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|pp=29-30}} Bela Lahiri theorizes that the constituents of a ''dwaimushyayana'' gotra may have differed during different periods, and Pushyamitra may have belonged to one of these gotras.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=33}}\n\nAccording to the Puranas, Pushyamitra became the king after killing his master [[Brihadratha]], the last Mauryan king.{{sfn|Thapar|2013|p=296}} However, the Buddhist text ''[[Divyavadana]]'' names Pushyamitra as the last Mauryan king.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=29}} This text appears to have confused Brihadratha with Pushyamitra.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=30}}\n\nH. C. Raychaudhuri theorized that the name \"Shunga\" is derived from the Sanskrit word for the fig tree.<ref>''Raychaudhari Hemchandra, \"Tha Audvijja Senani of the Harivansa?\", Indian culture, Vol. IV, 1938, P. 360-365''</ref>\n\n== Alleged persecution of Buddhists ==\n=== Buddhist accounts ===\n[[File:Sunga horseman Bharhut.jpg|thumb|Sunga horseman, Bharhut.]]\nBuddhist texts state that Pushyamitra cruelly persecuted the Buddhists. The earliest source to mention this is the 2nd Century CE text ''[[Ashokavadana]]'' (a part of ''[[Divyavadana]]''). According to this account, Pushyamitra (described as the last Mauryan king) wanted to be famous. His ministers advised him that as long as Buddhism remained the dominant faith, he would never be as famous as his ancestor [[Ashoka]], who had commissioned 84,000 [[stupa]]s. One advisor told him that he could become famous by destroying Buddhism. Pushyamitra then tried to destroy the [[Kukkutarama]] monastery, but it was saved by a miracle. He then proceeded to [[Sagala|Shakala]] in the north-west, where he offered a prize of one hundred ''dinara''s (gold coins) for every head of a Buddhist monk brought to him. Next, he proceeded to the Koshthaka kingdom, where a Buddhist [[yaksha]] named Damshtranivasin killed him and his army with help of another yaksha named Krimisha.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|pp=95-96}}{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=33}}\n\n{{quote|... Pushyamitra equipped a fourfold army, and intending to destroy the Buddhist religion, he went to the [[Kukkutarama]] (in [[Pataliputra]]). ... Pushyamitra therefore destroyed the [[sangharama]], killed the monks there, and departed. ... After some time, he arrived in [[Sagala|Sakala]], and proclaimed that he would give a ... reward to whoever brought him the head of a Buddhist monk.{{sf|Strong|1989|p=293}}}}\n\n''Vibhasa'', another 2nd century text, states that Pushyamitra burned Buddhist scriptures, killed Buddhist monks, and destroyed 500 monasteries in and around [[Kashmir]]. In this campaign, he was supported by yakshas, ''kumbhanda''s, and other demons. However, when he reached the [[Bodhi tree]], the deity of that tree took the form of a beautiful woman and killed him.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=96}} ''Shariputrapariprichha'', translated into Chinese between 317 and 420 CE also mentions this legend, but this particular version is more detailed, and describes eastern India (not Kashmir) as the center of Pushyamitra's anti-Buddhist campaign.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=96}}\n\nThe medieval-era ''Arya-Manjushri-Mula-Kalpa'' mentions a wicked and foolish king named Gomimukhya (\"cattle-faced\"), or Gomishanda (\"Gomin, the bull\"), who seized the territory from the east to Kashmir, destroying monasteries and killing monks. Ultimately, he and his officers were killed in the north by falling mountain rocks.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=96}}{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=33-34}} This king is identified with Pushyamitra by some scholars.<ref>{{cite book |first=Jayantanuja |last=Bandyopadhyaya |title=Class and Religion in Ancient India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gwUF11NRyT4C&pg=PA209 |year=2007 |publisher=Anthem |isbn=978-1-84331-332-8 |page=209 }}</ref>\n\nThe 16th-century Tibetan Buddhist historian [[Taranatha]] also states that Pushyamitra and his allies killed Buddhist monks and destroyed monasteries from ''madhyadesha'' (midland) to [[Jalandhar]]a. These activities wiped out the Buddhist doctrine from the north, within five years.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=96}}\n\n=== Authenticity of Buddhist claims ===\n[[File:Procession on Elephants. Bharhut, c. 100 BC. Indian Museum, Calcutta ei05-19.jpg|thumb|Men riding elephants. [[Bharhut]], Sunga period.]]\nBased on Buddhist tradition, some scholars believe that Pushyamitra was indeed a persecutor of the Buddhist faith. However, others believe that Buddhist scholars were biased against Pushyamitra, because he did not patronize them.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|pp=34-35}}\n\n[[Vincent Arthur Smith|V. A. Smith]] and H. P. Shastri believed that Pushyamitra's rebellion against the Maurya dynasty was a Brahminical reaction to the rise of Buddhism.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=34}} According to archaeologist [[John Marshall (archaeologist)|John Marshall]], there is evidence of some damage to Buddhist establishments at [[Takshashila]] around the time of Shunga rule. He also theorized that the [[Sanchi Stupa|Sanchi stupa]] was vandalized in 2nd century BCE (that is, during Pushyamitra's reign), before being rebuilt on a larger scale.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|pp=96-97}} G. R. Sharma, who excavated the Buddhist ruins at [[Kosambi|Kaushambi]], suggested that the destruction of the local monastery might have happened during the reign of Pushyamitra Shunga. P. K. Mishra believes that the damage to the [[Deur Kothar]] stupa is also datable to Pushyamitra's period.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=97}} H. C. Raychaudhari pointed out that Buddhist monuments were constructed at [[Bharhut]] during the Shunga rule.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=34}} However, according to N. N. Ghosh, these were constructed during the reign of later Shunga rulers, not Pushyamitra's period.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=97}}\n\nH. Bhattacharya theorized that Pushyamitra might have persecuted Buddhists for political, rather than religious, reasons: the politically active Buddhists probably supported the [[Indo-Greek Kingdom|Indo-Greek]] rivals of Pushyamitra, which might have prompted him to persecute them.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=100}} The ''Ashokavadana'' states that Pushyamitra declared a reward for killing Buddhist monks in [[Sagala|Shakala]] (present-day Sialkot), which was located near the Indo-Greek frontiers. According to K. P. Jayaswal, this further highlights a political motivation behind his alleged persecution of Buddhists.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|pp=99-100}}\n\nMany other scholars have expressed skepticism about the Buddhist claims of persecution by Pushyamitra. [[\u00c9tienne Lamotte]] points out that the Buddhist legends are not consistent about the location of Pushyamitra's anti-Buddhist campaign and his death.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=98}} The ''Ashokavadana'' claims that Pushyamitra offered ''dinara''s as a reward for killing Buddhist monks, but the ''dinara'' did not come into circulation in India before the 1st century CE. ''Ashokavadana'' also claims that Ashoka persecuted ''Nirgrantha''s ([[Ajivika]]s), which is an obvious fabrication, considering that Ashoka's edicts express tolerance towards all religious sects.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=99}} The Sri Lankan Buddhist text ''[[Mahavamsa]]'' suggests that several monasteries existed in present-day Bihar, Awadh and Malwa at the time Pushyamitra's contemporary [[Dutthagamani]] ruled in Lanka. This suggests that these monasteries survived Pushyamitra Shunga's reign.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=100}}\n\nH. C. Raychaudhury argued that Pushyamitra's overthrow of the Mauryans cannot be considered as a Brahmin uprising against Buddhist rule, as Brahmins did not suffer during the Mauryan rule: Ashoka's edicts mention the Brahmins before [[Shramana]]s, and the appointment of a Brahmin general (Pushyamitra) shows that the Brahmins were honoured at the Mauryan court.{{sfn|Lahiri|1974|p=34}} The fact that the ''Ashokavadana'' mentions Pushyamitra as a Mauryan further erodes its historical credibility, and weakens the hypothesis that he persecuted Buddhists because he was a Brahmin.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|p=99}} Raychaudhury also aruged that according to ''[[Malavikagnimitra]]'', a Buddhist nun named Bhagavati Kaushiki attended Pushyamitra's court, which indicates that they did not persecute Buddhists. However, Shankar Goyal states that there is no evidence of Kaushiki being a Buddhist nun.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rxpuAAAAMAAJ |title=Aspects of ancient Indian history and historiography |author=Shankar Goyal |publisher=Harman |year=1993 |isbn=9788185151694 |page=30 }}</ref> [[Romila Thapar]] writes that the lack of concrete archaeological evidence casts doubt on the claims of Buddhist persecution by Pushyamitra.<ref>A\u015boka and the Decline of the Mauryas by Romila Thapar, Oxford University Press, 1960 P200</ref>\n\nIt is possible that the Buddhist influence at the Mauryan court declined during Pushyamitra's reign, and the Buddhist monasteries and other institutions stopped receiving royal patronage. This change might have led to discontent among the Buddhists, resulting in exaggerated accounts of persecution.{{sfn|Simmons|Sarao|2010|pp=99-100}}\n\n[[Michael Witzel]] states that ''[[Manu Smriti|Manudharma]]'', which emphasizes the role of orthodox faith in state-craft and society, was first compiled under Pushyamitra's rule. According to Kaushik Roy, it was a Brahmanical reaction to the rise of Buddhism and Jainism.<ref name=\"roy\">Roy, Kaushik (2012). Hinduism and the Ethics of Warfare in South Asia: From Antiquity to the Present, p.109-118. Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|9781107017368}}</ref>\n\n== Succession of the throne ==\nPushyamitra Shunga was succeeded in 148 BCE by his son [[Agnimitra]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Ancient Indian History and Civilization |first=Sailendra Nath  |last=Sen |publisher=New Age International, 1999 |year=1999 |isbn=978-8-12241-198-0 |page=170 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wk4_ICH_g1EC&pg=PA170}}</ref>\n\n== In literature ==\nPushyamitra Shunga's history is recorded in the [[Harshacharita]] authored by [[B\u0101\u1e47abha\u1e6d\u1e6da]].\n\nAccording to ''Vicarasreni'' of [[Merutunga]], Pushyamitra or Pushpamitra got his throne in 204 BC.{{sfn|Jain|1991|p=85}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [[History of Buddhism]]\n* [[Indo-Greeks]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{ref begin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Jain |first=Kailash Chand |title=Lord Mah\u0101v\u012bra and His Times |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8-TxcO9dfrcC |date=1991 |publisher=[[Motilal Banarsidass]] | isbn=978-81-208-0805-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Simmons|first1=Caleb|last2=Sarao|first2=K. T. S.|editor1-last=Danver|editor1-first=Steven L.|title=Popular Controversies in World History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=slVobUjdzGMC |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-59884-078-0 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vdu1AAAAIAAJ |title=Indigenous states of northern India, circa 200 B.C. to 320 A.D. |first=Bela |last=Lahiri |publisher=University of Calcutta |year=1974 |page=31 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Strong|first1=John S.|authorlink = John S. Strong|title=The Legend of King A\u015boka : a study and translation of the A\u015bok\u0101vad\u0101na|date=1989|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton|isbn=0-691-01459-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kp9uaQTQ8h8C&pg=PA232|ref=harv}}\n* {{citation |last=Thapar |first=Romila |author-link=Romila Thapar |title=The Past Before Us|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aei9AAAAQBAJ |year=2013 |publisher=[[Harvard University Press]] |isbn=978-0-674-72651-2 }}\n{{ref end}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Shunga Empire|King of Shunga Dynasty]]\n| years = 185\u2013149 BCE\n| before = [[Mauryan Dynasty]]''<br /> '''[[Brihadratha Maurya]]''\n| after = [[Agnimitra]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shunga, Pushyamitra}}\n[[Category:2nd-century BC Indian monarchs]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:180s BC births]]\n[[Category:140s BC deaths]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4073:418:80cc:5aa:529d:a5f6:b409", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pushyamitra_Shunga"}
